Nvidia Corporation was founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem in Santa Clara, California. Initially focused on the graphics processing unit (GPU) market, Nvidia gained prominence in 1999 with the launch of the GeForce 256, marketed as the world’s first GPU. This product set a new standard for PC graphics and established Nvidia as a key player in the gaming industry.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia expanded through acquisitions and innovation, including purchasing 3dfx in 2000 and launching the CUDA parallel computing platform in 2006, which allowed GPUs to handle general-purpose computing tasks. This positioned the company at the forefront of high-performance computing.

In the 2010s, Nvidia strategically pivoted toward emerging technologies such as artificial intelligence (AI), deep learning, and autonomous vehicles. Its GPUs became essential in AI research and data centers, with platforms like the Nvidia DGX systems and the AI-focused A100 chips. Nvidia’s automotive partnerships helped push development in self-driving technologies.

In the gaming space, Nvidia continued to innovate with technologies like real-time ray tracing and the RTX series of graphics cards. It also expanded into cloud gaming with the launch of GeForce NOW.

By the early 2020s, Nvidia had become one of the most influential tech companies globally, driven by its dominance in GPU computing and AI infrastructure. Although it attempted to acquire chip designer Arm in 2020, the deal was abandoned in 2022 due to regulatory challenges.

Today, Nvidia is a leader in graphics, AI, and computing platforms across multiple industries.

claude
